Plan for Today

  • Discuss congressional careerism

  • Examine the incumbency advantage

  • Discuss the nationalization of politics

Congressional Careerism

  • The average length of time that a member of Congress spends is (for the 117th Congress):

    • 8.9 years (4.5 House terms) in the House

    • 11.0 years (1.8 Senate terms) in the Senate

  • The average age of members of Congress is:

    • 58.4 years in the House

    • 64.3 years in the Senate

  • Members are getting elected and staying in office for long periods of time

  • Early in American political history this was not the case

    • High congressional turnover

    • Much more state government focused

      • People might spend a term in the federal government and then go back to the state government

    • Recall, the control that the parties had on this process

      • Recruited candidates and played a significant role in the careers of politicians

  • The Progressive era changes

    • Secret (Australia) ballot

      • Made elected officials less reliant on parties

    • Overall decreases in party control

      • Increase in focus on constituents

    • Increased salaries of elected officials

      • Made the federal government a viable option for a career

Political Ambition

  • Members of Congress are “single-minded seekers of reelection” (Mayhew 1974)

  • Deciding to run for elected office is a strategic decision

    • There are benefits and costs that must be calculated before running

      • If the benefits outweigh the costs, then a person has an incentive to run

Types of Candidates

  • Individuals that run for Congress can be broken down into two groups:

    • Quality (professional) Candidates

      • These are candidates that have previous electoral experience

    • Amateur Candidates

      • These candidates have no previous electoral experience

  • Generally, quality candidates are going to outperform amateur candidates

    • There are exceptions such as AOC who defeated a Joe Crowley an incumbent

  • Certain amateur candidates will fare better than others

    • astronauts, actors, entertainers, athletes, war heroes, or business leaders

The Incumbency Advantage

  • Incumbents possess an advantage in elections

    • Why?

  • Institutional Advantages

    • MRAs

      • Franked mail

      • Staff

    • Name recognition

    • Credit claiming

    • Position taking

  • Money

    • Campaign fundraising skills

    • People want to donate to “winners”

    • Average cost to win a House seat is roughly 2 million and 14 million for the Senate

  • Redistricting

    • Districts drawn by state legislators tend to produce less competitive districts

      • Good for incumbents

How can Incumbents Lose?

  • National tides

    • Poor economic conditions

    • Midterm elections

      • No presidential coattails

  • Scandals

    • The average incumbent can expect to see their vote total drop by 5 to 11 points if they are involved in a scandal

      • That is a big margin for marginal candidates

  • Redistricting

  • Strategic retirements

The Nationalization of Politics

  • Voters rely more on simple partisan cues (i.e., party id) to make their vote choices

  • Split-ticket voting

    • Corresponds to a decrease in voting for one party’s candidate for one office and another party’s candidate for another office

    • Decreases with increased nationalization

  • What causes it?

    • Some scholars believe it is due to shifts in the electorate

      • Citizens become more loyal to a given party

    • Some scholars believe it is due to the elites

      • Party leaders in Congress have emphasized party loyalty as a requirement for members to advance in the chamber and receive rewards

Final Thoughts

  • Elected officials have increasingly turned to Congress as life long careers

  • Incumbents are greatly advantaged as it pertains to elections

  • Nationalization creates increases in partisanship
